      <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-gray-900">Remote Work Productivity: 15 Science-Backed Tips to Stay Focused at Home</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-8 text-gray-600">Distractions, procrastination, and the blur between work and life — working from home is hard. Here are 15 proven strategies that actually make a difference.</p>

      <div class="mt-10 prose prose-lg prose-gray max-w-none">
        <h2>1. Start Your Day With a "Commute"</h2>
        <p>No, not a real commute. A 10-15 minute morning routine that signals to your brain: work mode is about to start. Walk around the block, do light stretches, or just sit with a coffee away from your desk. The point is to create a clear transition between "home mode" and "work mode." Without it, you are rolling out of bed straight into emails — and your brain never fully shifts gears.</p>

        <h2>2. Get Dressed (Seriously)</h2>
        <p>You do not need a suit. But changing out of your pajamas into actual clothes — even casual ones — has a measurable effect on your psychological readiness for work. This is called "enclothed cognition": what you wear affects how you think and perform. Jeans and a clean shirt are plenty.</p>

        <h2>3. Designate a Work-Only Zone</h2>
        <p>Your brain associates locations with activities. If you work from your bed or couch, your brain now associates those places with work stress as well as relaxation — and neither function works well. Even in a studio apartment, designate one specific spot (even a specific chair at the kitchen table) as "the office." Never do leisure activities there.</p>

        <h2>4. Use the Pomodoro Technique</h2>
        <p>The simplest and most effective focus method: work for 25 minutes, break for 5. Repeat four times, then take a longer 15-30 minute break. The short timer makes starting feel easier ("I can do anything for 25 minutes"), and the forced breaks prevent burnout. Apps: Tomato Timer (free web), Focus Keeper (iOS), or just your phone timer.</p>

        <h2>5. Turn Off All Non-Essential Notifications</h2>
        <p>Every notification — Slack ping, email alert, phone buzz — costs you an average of 23 minutes to fully refocus (University of California, Irvine study). Put your phone in another room during deep work. Turn off desktop notifications for everything except critical messages. Use Focus modes (iOS) or Focus Assist (Windows).</p>

        <h2>6. Time Block Your Day</h2>
        <p>Instead of a to-do list, schedule specific blocks of time for specific types of work. "Writing: 9-11am. Emails: 11-11:30am. Deep work: 1-4pm." This prevents the "what should I do next?" decision fatigue that kills productivity. Plan your blocks the night before for best results.</p>

        <h2>7. Set Hard Start and Stop Times</h2>
        <p>One of the biggest WFH traps: the workday never ends. Set a firm "shutdown" time and stick to it. When the time hits, close your laptop, and do not open it again. Without this boundary, work expands to fill all available time — and burnout follows.</p>

        <h2>8. Use Website Blockers for Deep Work</h2>
        <p>Willpower alone is not reliable. Use tools like Freedom, Cold Turkey, or SelfControl to block distracting websites during your focus blocks. Block social media, news sites, Reddit, YouTube — anything that pulls you away. Set it and forget it.</p>

        <h2>9. Take a Proper Lunch Break Away From Your Desk</h2>
        <p>Eating lunch at your desk while scrolling through emails is not a break. Step away. Eat in a different room. Go outside if you can. A real break recharges your mental batteries for the afternoon. 15 minutes is a minimum; 30-45 is ideal.</p>

        <h2>10. Move Your Body Every Hour</h2>
        <p>Set a recurring hourly alarm. When it goes off, stand up and do something — stretch, walk to the kitchen, do 10 squats, anything. Micro-movements throughout the day are more effective at preventing back pain and fatigue than one big workout at the end of the day.</p>

        <h2>11. Use Music Strategically</h2>
        <p>Music with lyrics competes with language processing in your brain — bad for writing or coding. Instrumental music (lo-fi, classical, ambient, video game soundtracks) enhances focus without the distraction. Try Brain.fm or a lo-fi playlist on Spotify.</p>

        <h2>12. End Your Day With a Shutdown Ritual</h2>
        <p>Spend 5 minutes reviewing what you accomplished, writing down your top 3 priorities for tomorrow, and closing all your tabs and apps. This signals to your brain that work is truly done and prevents mental "open loops" from running all evening.</p>

        <h2>13. Stay Socially Connected</h2>
        <p>Remote work can be isolating. Schedule at least one social interaction per day that is not a work meeting — a quick call with a friend, a coffee with a neighbor. Loneliness is both a productivity killer and a health risk. Do not underestimate it.</p>

        <h2>14. Separate Work Devices From Personal Devices</h2>
        <p>If possible, use a separate computer or at least a separate user profile for work. When you switch to your personal profile, work apps and notifications are gone. This creates a hard digital boundary that mirrors a physical one.</p>

        <h2>15. Measure Output, Not Hours</h2>
        <p>Remote work frees you from "butt-in-seat" culture. Focus on what you actually produce, not how many hours you look busy. Define 2-3 key results for each day. When those are done, you are done — even if it is 3pm. This mindset shift is the ultimate WFH productivity upgrade.</p>

